entry.title: Pterostylis aciculiformis
entry.content: Although this plant is just outside the boundaries of the National Park, they are also found within the park. This plant appeared spontaneously this year - I have not seen it before in this location. Note the second photo for close-up of the labellum.

entry.title: Corunastylis morrisii

entry.title: Corunastylis archeri
entry.content: Flowering time Nov - March. Grows in many habitats. Flower dorsal sepal and petals lack hairs, labellum is fringed with medium to longish hairs.

entry.title: Caladenia transitoria
entry.content: Flowering period Oct - Nov. Plant usually about 100mm tall and difficult to see in habitat. Labellum has dark purple calli and petals usually yellowish-green.

entry.title: Caladenia cucullata
entry.content: Flowers are white, labellum has red to purple calli. Common in inland areas.

entry.title: Grevillea micrantha
entry.content: The Brisbane Ranges form has leaves with granules confined to the veins on upper surface and broader grooves on undersurface. Found mainly in western and central Victoria. The climate is hot dry summers, cold wet winters, rainfall around 500mm annually.

entry.title: Grevillea micrantha
entry.content: Commonly known as Small-leaf Grevillea. The flowers are white to pale pink and often hidden in the dull green foliage.

entry.title: Thelymitra spp.
entry.content: This is a natural hybrid between Thelymitra holmesii and Thelymitra ixioides. It was photographed at the edge of a swamp area.

entry.title: Grevillea steiglitziana
entry.content: This grevillea is a low spreading shrub with shiny, lightly toothed, holly-like leaves and bright red toothbrush flowers. It is found in Victoria, mostly confined to the Brisbane Ranges between Geelong & Bacchus marsh. Grows in dry, open eucalypt forest

entry.title: Pterostylis smaragdyna
entry.content: Flowers in Winter (Jun - Aug), favours low flats, well drained - loamy soil in open forest. Labellum contains small bristles and retracts when disturbed. Lateral sepals touching at base of flower.
